review_blob: 330 ml bottle courtesy of nate2g. Lovely chocolate aroma. Flavour is a bit watery, thin but pleasant. Some autolysis. This one is probably getting a bit old, I foumd it hiding on the cellar...

330 ml bottle, courtesey of Nate2g.
This has been aged a bit and without having tried it young I think that has improved it. Clean raisiney flavours and aroma with a lot of toffee and some chocolate as well. Very drinkable.

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob: Golden, high carbonation. Aroma of clean malt and a mix of hops that seems german to me. Alcohol on the nose too. Flavour is much better, full mouthfeel with big clean malt and zingy hop flavours, good bitterness. lots of alcohol warmth.

decent wildish ale. sour aroma and flavour, some other funky things going on as well. the main drawback for this beer is that the bitterness is too high, in my opinion. the bitterness does not mingle all that well with the sourness.

not super impressed with this one. the belgian-ess is a bit odd, kinda musty without being farmhouse musty. cherries are quite subdued and if I didnt know they were there I would probably not have picked them out. interesting experiment though and with a bit of tweeking it could be quite good. Id like to see it as a cleaner belgian with more cherry character.

pretty good. clean. big malt with good hoppyness. bit too malty for my taste in this style, gets a bit too much towards the end but the high bitterness helps with drinkablity. good standard DIPA without being too impresive.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: on tap at monks kettle. good stuff. big raisiny, malty, phenolic and slightly fruite aromas and flavours. big malty backbone but nice dry mouthfeel. only flaw is the alcoholic notes, a bit of age would make it really good.
farmhouse ale for sure, spice, herbal, earthy. got some ginger on the aroma. not sure what makes it norvegian (thats what the menu at monk kettle said) but it was good. id call it a saison
interesting malty, slightly fruity and slightly sour aromas and flavours that can mainly be described as earthy. pretty good, not great but excellent with the lamb burger I had

decent, but no IPA in my book.
fresh but still malt dominated and even that is a bit subtle.
pretty decent, think belgian wit with all the usual characterestics but a bit blander.
subtle aroma of malt, diacetyl and hops, in that order. flavour is a bit empty, again diacetyl but its faint. kinda bland but not too bad, drinkable for sure
beer_name: R & B Red Devil Pale Ale

review_blob: pretty decent american IPA but is let down by a rather weak aroma. nice flavours and super mouthfeel.

2007 vintage. Brown, not much head but good lacing. Complex aroma of malty bread, spice, some oxidazion, stonefruits, banana and a hint of alcohol. Flavour gets a bit of dry cocoa, more spice, more bread and something udefinable that lingers on the back palate, very nice. The mouthfeel starts out a bit weak but then explodes and lingers, interesting. I cant taste the alcohol but I can feel the warmth. A true sipper, perfect with a good book and a nice hunk of camenbert.

big malt, big hops, whats not to like? great stuff. you could call this a barley wine I suppose but given the relatively slender body (much fatter than a IIPA though) I think double pale ale is the correct deScription.
beer_name: Flying Dog Double Dog Double Pale Ale

review_blob: liquorice and chocolate. I cant describe it better than the label. it taste like one of those liqourice logs with choclolate stuffing that I used to eat as a kids. I like it.
beer_name: Flying Dog Horn Dog Barley Wine

review_blob: after 16 hours at the office im happy to find curb your enthusiasm on the telly and a mikkeller black in the beer fridge. man, this is one intense beer! nose is dark choc and stonefruit, like imperial black forrest cake. the palate is a little bit harsh but extremely smooth for the 17.5%. I love it for what it is, but its lacking drinkability..
pretty good but not very belgian... arome is aged malt and chocolate, not bad. flavour picks up a few more esters and phenols but still not all that belgian. its good but a boit too clean.
clean malty aroma with a hint of fruitiness. malt flavours with some spicy citrussy hops. one word sums up this beer: clean. Nothing great but very well made and really drinkable

Beer or Cider? Im not sure I would hav ebeen able to tell the difference if the label hadnt told me, and it doesnt! It speaks of both beer and cider! anyways, this is good. Smells like a flanders sour red ale: sour, oaky, really inviting. The apple is more evident in the flavour and the malt comes through much better as well. I really like this, gota find some more beers from Thorogoods! Cheers to nate2g for the bottle!
beer_name: Thorogoods Billy Bs Golden Malted Apple Beer

review_blob: great stuff. malty aroma wit a knife sharp citrussy hoppiness. big malty mouthfeel with an intense bitterness and cut-through rather one dimensional hoppiness. pretty high carbonation for the style but it makes it really drinkable.

this is really good. intense, but not cloying, rum and raisiny aromas and flavours. big but dry mouthfeel. very disguised touch of alcohol. phenols galore without being overpowering. floaties are very hard to avoid though.

fizzy golden, no head retention. first smell of this didnt seem promising in my nostrils, dominated by spicy phenols, I prefer my tripels more dominated by fruity esters. the taste was really good though, mainly fruity and perfect balance of sweet flavours with a dry palate. going back to the aroma it fruitens up while its warming up. alcohol is certainly there but it is not head ache inducing. quite tasty! Cheer to nate2g for the bottle

reddish brown, a few floaties courtesey of my appauling pouring technique. suprisingly mostly chocolate on the nose a bit of malt and very little belgianess. burnt sugar flavour and a few more esters and phenols. dry mouthfeel. pretty good but not very belgian.

rich, malty sweet and peaty aroma. same flavours but the peat springs to life in the end palate as the carbonation tickles the tongue. mouthfeel is a bit on the lighter side. overall its pretty tasty! Skaal nate2g!

I dont think Ive tried the galaxy hop before so didnt quite know what to expect. the nose is lovely, citrus, grass, fresh. flavour has some maltiness and the same hop notes with a predominantly grassy linger. The mouthfeel is lacking a bit but that is the price you often have to pay for 4.8%. With a bit more body and alcohol this could carry a lot more flavour, but Im loving the fact that this is weak enough to drink a 6 pack and yet really hoppy and flavoursome. Cheers nate2g!
beer_name: Bridge Road Single Hop IPA: Galaxy

review_blob: this is seriously malty, chewy and raisiny. I get some phenols and belgian esters behind the brick wall of malt but it is certainly clear whos winning the battle. i think its a bit too heavy and carbonation is too low to be "to style" but never the less it is damn tasty! Cheers nate2g!
golden, not much head. aroma and flavour of sweet chewy malt and tropical fruits: mandarins, mango, orange, pinapple maybe. pretty tasty and refreshing.

330 ml bottle, courtesey of nate2g.
Excellent stout. Aroma is packed with malty coffee and more dominant chocolate. roasty flavours with a bit of fruity esters although the fermentation characters are very clean. Slightly hoppy tart finish. good bitterness but a bit overcarbonated. Really enjoying it.
obviously awesome packaging. sweet bready malty and spicy hop aroma. same sweet flavour with a pappery hoppiness. this is a big beer that gets a bit cloying, a little cripser and it would be awesome.

330 ml bottle, courtesey of nate2g, cheers mate! 
pours a hazy orange which is not as unapealing as it sounds. toasted caramel and citrus, fruity aroma, not bad. flavour is malt dominated but with a fair bit of undefined hoppy flavours too. crisp. strong bitterness, great aftertaste.

330 ml bottle, courtesey of nate2g, cheers mate!
nose is massive caramelized malt with phenols and esters galore. the taste is much the same, with and added element of tartness and a bit of hops. oh and a fair bit of chocolate. nice bitterness, carbonation and lingering flavours.I like it.
pretty decent drop. chocolate and toffee aroma but also an estery bubblegummy note in the background which I dont particularly care for. Roasty flavours with a nice mouthfeel. very drinkable.

Im getting no hops on the nose, belgian esters and phenols. the hops show themselves more in the flavour and mingle rather well with the belgianess, the overall picture is sort of tart though and it doesnt quite stack up to greatness. decent though.

smells excactly like chcolate milkshake, nice. flavour is also very chocolatetey but, and I cant believe Im saying this, the hops are too much. the flavour is just not balanced and it turns out harsh and solventy from the alcohol. pretty good though.
beer_name: Left Hand Wake Up Dead Imperial Stout

review_blob: I wouldnt call this an IPA, let alone double IPA, much too dark and rich caramel malty. (double) amber ale Id say. Never the less, pretty tasty. Rich caramelly malt backed up by sharp citrus hoppiness.
decent stout, but imo a bit weak for the style, I am missing mouthfeel and flavour. Aroma is pretty good, milk chocolate and caramel, follows through in the flavour but too weak.
not quite as bland as expected. yeasty aroma, almost belgian, same sort of flavour but kinda crisp. definitely drink this over any green bottled lager out there.

very pleasantly suprised with this one, did not expect much, other coopers beers Ive had have been pretty ordinary. good solid stout with some funky fruityness going on. Some hoppiness which is pretty funky too, could this be the fabled Pride of Ringwood??

great beer. classic stout aromas but more mellow and mixed with belgian esters and phenols, very interesting but alcohol is a bit to evident. flavours are much the same, alcohol more mellow though, and incredible smooth mouthfell. Had this for breakfast, perfect choice.
good stout. not quite imperial for me though, sort of in between. very drinkable
beer_name: Bear Republic Big Bear Black Stout

review_blob: murky rusty brwon/red. oxidized aroma, like sherry, apples. Flavour is fruity and slightly sour, quite enjoyed this.
great beer but not quite worth all the hype. coffee wasnt nearly as dominant as I expected and the alcohol was too evident and harsh. but in all, an excellent imperial stout
quite floral and fruity hoppiness. big caramel sweetness to support the IBUs which certainly can be tasted. well balanced. enjoyed it altough it was a bit dated.

massive chocolate, especially in the aroma. smells, and tastes, like high quality dark chocolate mixed with a bit of bread. got some nice underlaying esters as well without being dominant. nice mouthfeel and bitterness. would be great with deserts but I have always had it on its own.

2009. smells like a shandy (lemonade and lager): corn, cirtus hops and malt sweetness. got some kind of funky esters going on too. a fair bit of hops but they are not particular pleasant, neither is the malt, too sweet. lingering liqorice bitterness. pretty average but I think it will develop with some age to melt the flavours together.

Great I.P.A. This one was a bit travelled and I will definitely try it again and re-rate it fresh. fruity aromas and flavours, more diverse than the standard citrus/pine US IPA and nice underlaying maltiness.

the best Unibrou ive had so far. it made it all the way to NZ without tasting old and musty. nice esters and phenols on a firm malty backbone with some restrainted roastiness. very enjoyable the only thing I would fault this one for is that it was a bit too sweet and Im not sure I would have enjoyed the entire bottle.
very easy drinking stout and no flaws that I can pick. But it is kinda thin and watery, too carbonated. good flavor and aroma but weak and too faint.

I count the packaging as appearence in this one. sparkling ruby red. oxidized aroma, like sherry, apples, this is not what I expected. Flavour is fruity and slightly sour, again this is unexpected and initially I am disappointed. the beer grows on me throughout the bottle though and by the end of it I start realizing that it is not too old, off or oxidized, this is all intentional and the beer goes from being disappointing to a pleasant surprise.
